  "If 2.5 g of Mg reacts with excess HCl, what volume of H2 at STP is produced?": "Steps:\n1. Reaction: Mg + 2 HCl \u2192 MgCl2 + H2\n2. Moles Mg = mass / M_r = 2.5 / 24.305 = 0.1029 mol\n3. Stoichiometry: 1 mol Mg \u2192 1 mol H2, so moles H2 = 0.1029 mol\n4. At STP, 1 mol gas = 22.414 L, so V = 0.1029 * 22.414 = 2.306 L \u2248 2.31 L\n\nLaTeX: $n_{Mg}=\\frac{2.5}{24.305}=0.1029\\ mol;\\ V_{H_2}=0.1029\\times22.414=2.31\\ L$",
  "Provide the pKa trend for carboxylic acids vs phenols with references.": "Summary:\nCarboxylic acids are generally stronger acids (pKa ~ 4-5) compared to phenols (pKa ~ 9-10) due to resonance stabilization of the carboxylate anion and better delocalization. Phenoxide ion is less stabilized. For authoritative references consult standard organic chemistry textbooks (e.g., March's Advanced Organic Chemistry) or NIST data.\n\nLaTeX/short: $pK_a(\\text{carboxylic acid})\\approx4-5;\\ pK_a(\\text{phenol})\\approx9-10$"
